@*
    Edit a numeric value the user-facing way. The bound SiValue is
    always canonical SI for the quantity (Length in m, Density in
    kg/m³, etc.); this component looks up the Job's UnitSystem from
    the cascade, projects SI into the right unit for the visible
    <input>, and on every keystroke converts the typed value back to
    SI before raising @bind-SiValue's change callback.

    Special cases mirror <UnitFormatted>:
      * EnkiQuantity.Angle — pass-through. The DB stores degrees,
        the user types degrees, no conversion either direction.
      * OverrideUnit — caller pinned a specific unit (tubular OD =
        in / mm). UnitConverter.ToSi runs with the override instead
        of the preset.

    Oilfield-specific quantities (CurvatureRate, GammaRay, sonic
    transit time, …) are NOT supported as inputs today — they're
    computed by Marduk or sourced from logs, never typed. Passing
    one throws so the call site gets fixed rather than silently
    losing precision.

    State-machine note:
      The visible string is held verbatim in `_lastDisplayString`
      so a partial input like "12." while the user is typing "12.5"
      isn't clobbered by a re-projection round-trip. We only
      re-project from SiValue when the parent changes it
      externally (or when the cascading UnitSystem flips). This
      mirrors the standard pattern Blazor's InputBase uses for
      typed-but-unparsed values.

    Commit semantics:
      The bound SiValue updates on commit (blur / Enter / Tab) via
      @onchange — NOT per-keystroke. This avoids churning the parent
      render cycle on every character, which broke Syncfusion grid
      edit cells (parent re-render mid-typing reset the row context
      to the pre-edit snapshot, reverting the user's input as soon as
      the parsed value differed from the original). Save buttons
      trigger blur first, so the bound model is up-to-date by the
      time submit runs.
*@

<span class="enki-unit-input">
    @* @onchange (commit-on-blur) rather than @oninput (per-keystroke).
       In a Syncfusion grid edit cell the per-keystroke callback churns
       the grid's row-clone bookkeeping, which can reset the cell
       context back to the pre-edit snapshot mid-typing — the user sees
       their input reverted as soon as the parsed value differs from
       the original (the early-return on equal values hides this until
       the first "real" change). Commit-on-blur avoids the churn
       entirely. Save buttons trigger blur first, so bound models are
       still up-to-date by the time submit runs. *@
    <input type="number"
           class="@CssClass enki-mono"
           value="@_lastDisplayString"
           step="@StepText"
           min="@MinText"
           max="@MaxText"
           disabled="@Disabled"
           @onchange="OnInput" />
    @if (ShowUnit && _abbrev.Length > 0)
    {
        <span class="enki-unit-input-suffix enki-mono">@_abbrev</span>
    }
</span>

